  "title": "Spinal cord",
  "body_html": "<b>Key Points</b><br /><br /><ul><li>The spinal cord originates as a continuation of the medulla oblongata in the brainstem</li><li>The spinal cord terminates at L3 at birth, and L1/L2 by the age of 21. </li><li>It has 2 enlargements. One in the cervical region for the brachial plexus and the second in the lumbosacral region for the lumbar and sacral plexuses.</li><li>Remember that spinal segments are different to vertebral levels. See the table below.</li><li>It is supplied by three arteries. A single anterior artery and a pair of posterior spinal arteries.</li></ul><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti453b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti453.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Organisation of arterial supply to the spinal cord</div><br /><i>Illustration of spinal cord anatomy and blood supply</i><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti170b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti170.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Anterior view</div><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti171b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti171.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Lateral view view</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/swb457b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/swb457.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinal cord'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/swb457b.png'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodylinks\"></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodymedia\"></div>\n\n\n<div id=\"categorynum\">1</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategorynum\">4</div>\n\n<div id=\"categoryname\">Anatomy</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategoryname\">Systems & applied anatomy</div>\n<div id=\"mybody\">\n\n<div id=\"body_content\">\n<b>Key Points</b><br /><br /><ul><li>The spinal cord originates as a continuation of the medulla oblongata in the brainstem</li><li>The spinal cord terminates at L3 at birth, and L1/L2 by the age of 21. </li><li>It has 2 enlargements. One in the cervical region for the brachial plexus and the second in the lumbosacral region for the lumbar and sacral plexuses.</li><li>Remember that spinal segments are different to vertebral levels. See the table below.</li><li>It is supplied by three arteries. A single anterior artery and a pair of posterior spinal arteries.</li></ul><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti453b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti453.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Organisation of arterial supply to the spinal cord</div><br /><i>Illustration of spinal cord anatomy and blood supply</i><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti170b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti170.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Anterior view</div><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti171b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti171.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Lateral view view</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/swb457b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/swb457.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinal cord'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/swb457b.png'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER></div>\n\n\n<BR><BR><br><br>",
